      Tuna bonds
   =20
 =20
If you are a big international bank and you are hired to arrange financing =
for the government of Mozambique to fund a project involving fishing boats,=
 and the government officials on the deal say =E2=80=9Chey, you know what, =
when you raise half a billion dollars from investors for this project, inst=
ead of sending the money to an official government account, why don=E2=80=
=99t you wire it directly to our shipbuilding contractor in Abu Dhabi, they=
=E2=80=99ll handle =E2=80=A6=C2=A0a few =E2=80=A6=C2=A0transactions for us,=
=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s a good idea for you to do due diligence on that cont=
ractor, check them out, see what they=E2=80=99re all about. Ideally the due=
 diligence report will come back saying =E2=80=9Cyes, that contractor is gr=
eat, the guy in charge is an upstanding character who does scrupulous work=
=C2=A0for various government projects and everyone he works with vouches fo=
r his integrity.=E2=80=9D But it will not say that!=C2=A0Come on. It will s=
ay this:The Bank=E2=80=99s financial crime compliance group commissioned an=
d received a third-party diligence report that quoted an anonymous source d=
escribing the Intermediary=E2=80=99s principal (=E2=80=9CIntermediary Princ=
ipal=E2=80=9D) as a =E2=80=9Cmaster of kickbacks=E2=80=9D and included othe=
r information, including:=E2=80=9CAll sources we spoke to about [Intermedia=
ry Principal] were confident of his past and continued involvement in offer=
ing and receiving bribes and kickbacks=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Craised concern=
s about the integrity of [Intermediary Principal=E2=80=99s] business practi=
ces,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9C[Intermediary Principal] was heavily involv=
ed in corrupt practices.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CAnother banking source close to a=
 Lebanese commercial bank that previously dealt with [Intermediary Principa=
l and his brother] and the [Intermediary] group of companies stated: =E2=80=
=98[Intermediary Principal] is a first-class deal maker and an expert in ki=
ckbacks, bribery and corruption.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9DYeah I mean those are pro=
bably endorsements on his LinkedIn. That=E2=80=99s probably=C2=A0his job de=
scription on LinkedIn, =E2=80=9CMaster of Kickbacks at Self-Employed.=E2=80=
=9D If you=E2=80=99re in the business of shortstopping nine-figure payments=
 between big investment banks and emerging-market governmental projects, yo=
u are almost necessarily in the business of diverting a big chunk of those =
payments for bribes. Here:In total, Credit Suisse transferred $547,463,200,=
 including $446,950,800 that it arranged and $100,512,400 that was arranged=
 by VTB, to the Intermediary, from which bank records of the Intermediary r=
eflect that improper payments were made to Mozambican officials and the Int=
ermediary Agent and others, and kickbacks to the CS Bankers.Shortly after t=
he first transfer to the Intermediary in March 2013, Intermediary bank reco=
rds indicate transfers of over $80 million to accounts controlled by Mozamb=
ican government officials and others relating to the transaction. The trans=
fers included a transfer of $50 million from which a relative of a high-lev=
el government official shared part of the payment with key government offic=
ials, who approved the transaction and authorized the-then Minister of Fina=
nce to sign the guarantee. Intermediary bank records reflect additional imp=
roper payments, including, for example, $13 million paid to government offi=
cials holding senior positions at ProIndicus and a $5 million payment to a =
senior official who reported to the-then President of Mozambique.These quot=
es are from the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission order against Credi=
t Suisse Group AG, which raised a bunch of money for Mozambican government =
projects, much of which ended up being spent on bribes. Yesterday Credit Su=
isse agreed to pay a total of=C2=A0$475 million to the SEC, the U.S. Depart=
ment of Justice=C2=A0and=C2=A0the U.K. Financial Conduct Authority to settl=
e these charges. We talked about this case  back in 2019; it is the origin =
of my long-running not-legal-advice-but-still-worth-considering suggestion =
that, if you are doing bribes, you should not call them =E2=80=9Cchickens.=
=E2=80=9D Not that you should say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m a master of bribes a=
nd kickbacks=E2=80=9D either. Use=C2=A0good=C2=A0euphemisms.We talked about=
 it in 2019 because three of the Credit Suisse bankers involved in arrangin=
g the loans were arrested and charged with, among other things, knowingly r=
aising money to pay these bribes but also=C2=A0taking bribes themselves. (T=
hey eventually pleaded guilty.) The basic model here is:=09Credit Suisse is=
 a big bank and has lots of money.=09Mozambique is a country and has a reas=
onable amount of capacity to borrow money.=09Some Mozambican government off=
icials would like to put millions of dollars into their personal bank accou=
nts.=09The officials could go to Credit Suisse and say =E2=80=9Cwe would li=
ke to borrow money on behalf of the country of Mozambique and then steal it=
 for ourselves.=E2=80=9D=09But Credit Suisse would say no to that propositi=
on, because (1) that would get it in legal and reputational trouble and (2)=
 that proposition has a lot of=C2=A0credit risk; if you lend money to a cou=
ntry and the money is stolen the country might not be able to pay you back.=
=09But there=E2=80=99s not really such a thing as =E2=80=9Cgoing to Credit =
Suisse=E2=80=9D to ask for money. You go to a=C2=A0person=C2=A0at Credit Su=
isse.=09So the officials went to their friendly Credit Suisse relationship =
banker and said =E2=80=9Cwe would like to borrow money from your employer (=
Credit Suisse) on behalf of our employer (Mozambique) and then steal it for=
 ourselves. We need someone inside Credit Suisse to help us do that. Why no=
t you? We will make it worth your while by giving you some of the money we =
steal.=E2=80=9D=09The bankers were like =E2=80=9Csure we could use a few mi=
llion extra dollars, we will help you trick our bank into lending money to =
Mozambique for you to steal.=E2=80=9DObviously this is bad. Obviously the m=
ain victim here is Mozambique, which has borrowed money (and has to repay i=
t) but not received (much of) the money because it went to bribes instead. =
But of course the main bad actors here are the Mozambican government offici=
als who stole the money. Meanwhile the supporting bad actors here are the C=
redit Suisse bankers who helped steal the money and took bribes for their t=
rouble. But of course a secondary victim here=C2=A0is Credit Suisse, which =
was tricked (by its own bankers and the Mozambican officials) into making l=
oans on false pretenses that were unlikely to be paid back. Both principals=
 here are victims, and both were victimized by their own (and each others=
=E2=80=99) agents.There is a third set of victims here: Credit Suisse didn=
=E2=80=99t keep a lot of the loans on its books, but sold them off to other=
 investors. (Later, it exchanged the loans into bonds.) The other investors=
 were told things about the loans =E2=80=94=C2=A0about Mozambique=E2=80=99s=
 borrowing capacity under IMF rules, etc., but also more basically that the=
 loans were being used to build a tuna fishing fleet, not to pay bribes =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0that turned out not to be true. The perpetrators of these lies =
were, you know, Credit Suisse (and its corrupt bankers) and the government =
of Mozambique (and its corrupt officials). If you are an investor and you g=
et an offering memo from the Republic of Mozambique with Credit Suisse on t=
he cover as lead arranger, and everything in the offering memo is a lie and=
 the loans default, you will conclude that (1) you were defrauded and (2) M=
ozambique and Credit Suisse jointly did the defrauding. In a sense neither =
=E2=80=9CMozambique=E2=80=9D nor =E2=80=9CCredit Suisse=E2=80=9D could have=
 done the defrauding =E2=80=94=C2=A0some particular humans employed by the =
government of Mozambique and Credit Suisse did the defrauding =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but you will not split hairs.One interesting question to ask, in reading=
 these settlements, is: What did Credit Suisse do wrong? One obvious possib=
ility is: Credit Suisse (through its corrupt bankers) arranged to pay bribe=
s. This is bad because it effectively stole money from the people of Mozamb=
ique to give to corrupt government officials (and its own corrupt bankers).=
 Mozambique was left with a debt that it couldn=E2=80=99t repay, and didn=
=E2=80=99t have much to show for it. The Credit Suisse bankers victimized t=
he people of Mozambique, and Credit Suisse as a firm is responsible for the=
ir actions. This is sort of the line that the U.K. FCA takes:Mark Steward, =
Executive Director of Enforcement and Market Oversight at the FCA, said:=E2=
=80=98The FCA=E2=80=99s fine reflects the impact of these tainted transacti=
ons which included a debt crisis and economic harm for the people of Mozamb=
ique. The fine would have been higher if not for Credit Suisse agreeing to =
provide the debt write-off of US$200 million. The FCA will continue to purs=
ue serious financial crime control failings by regulated firms.=E2=80=99Bet=
ween October 2012 to March 2016, Credit Suisse failed to properly manage th=
e risk of financial crime within its emerging markets business. It had suff=
icient information from which it should have appreciated the unacceptable r=
isk of bribery associated with the two Mozambican loans and a bond exchange=
 related to government sponsored projects.=C2=A0You could imagine Credit Su=
isse defending against this charge by saying =E2=80=9Cno, we are victims he=
re just as much as Mozambique is; after all=C2=A0we=C2=A0gave Mozambique=C2=
=A0money under false pretenses; how were we supposed to know that it was fo=
r bribes?=E2=80=9D But the answer to that is, you were definitely supposed =
to know, there were tons of red flags. That due diligence report that I quo=
ted at the beginning is one of them. There was actually some good news in t=
hat report! The SEC says:The information provided to the compliance team in=
 their diligence efforts also included that the Intermediary Principal=E2=
=80=99s business was being conducted =E2=80=9Cin a more classical way, more=
 in compliance with the rules of ethics.=E2=80=9D A source also reported th=
at UAE authorities were not aware of information tying the Intermediary to =
corrupt practices, and that the Intermediary Principal had been removed fro=
m a screening service due to the age of some of the allegations against him=
.But once you get to =E2=80=9Cmaster of kickbacks,=E2=80=9D you don=E2=80=
=99t really get to rely on conflicting reports of business conducted =E2=80=
=9Cin a more classical way.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The FCA says:Credit Suisse conduc=
ted due diligence, including enhanced due diligence, on the relevant entiti=
es and individuals related to the transactions, and other key functions and=
 committees were involved in reviewing and approving the transactions. Howe=
ver, Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s consideration of the above risk factors was in=
adequate because it gave insufficient weight to the risk factors individual=
ly and failed to adequately consider them holistically. Credit Suisse faile=
d to recognise that a corruption =E2=80=98red flag=E2=80=99 will often be =
=E2=80=93 rather than direct evidence of corruption or bribery =E2=80=93 ap=
parent from the context of the transaction, sector, jurisdiction and counte=
rparty. Instead of aggregating relevant risks, it considered them in isolat=
ion.So Credit Suisse failed to properly check on its corrupt bankers, so it=
 is responsible for their bribes. If you take this line =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=
 Credit Suisse effectively stole from the people of Mozambique =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then obviously part of the punishment should be that it gives the money =
back to Mozambique. Which is in fact  part of the result here:As part of th=
e settlement, Credit Suisse agreed to forgive $200 million of debt owed by =
Mozambique.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThis marks a first in that relief is flowing to t=
he people of a country,=E2=80=9D said Matthew Herrington, a lawyer for Cred=
it Suisse at Paul Hastings LLP. =E2=80=9CI am proud to have been part of th=
is resolution.=E2=80=9DA related theory of what Credit Suisse did wrong was=
: It let itself be taken advantage of. If your view is that Credit Suisse i=
s a victim here because it was tricked by its own bankers into lending mone=
y on false pretenses, that=E2=80=99s still bad! If you are a bank you are s=
upposed to have processes in place to make sure that your own bankers don=
=E2=80=99t steal from you! If they=C2=A0do=C2=A0steal from you, not only ar=
e you out the money they stole, but you=C2=A0should=C2=A0expect banking reg=
ulators to fine you some more money, because that is bad banking practice. =
Part of the job of a bank is not to get its money stolen, and if you fail a=
t that job there are legal consequences.=C2=A0Of course it=E2=80=99s mostly=
 not Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s money that was stolen, since the loans were sy=
ndicated to investors. Another possible theory of what Credit Suisse did wr=
ong=C2=A0is: Credit Suisse lied to investors about the details and legality=
 of these loans (and bonds[1]). This is the =E2=80=9Ceverything is securiti=
es fraud=E2=80=9D theory: If you lend money to a country that will be used =
to pay bribes, and you issue bonds to investors to fund that loan, and you =
don=E2=80=99t tell the investors about the bribes, then you have committed =
securities fraud against them. This is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of the normal wa=
y American law works these days? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and so the SEC and DOJ most=
ly take this line. The SEC:"Credit Suisse provided investors with incomplet=
e and misleading disclosures despite being uniquely positioned to understan=
d the full extent of Mozambique's mounting debt and serious risk of default=
 based on its prior lending arrangements," said Anita B. Bandy, Associate D=
irector of the SEC's Division of Enforcement. "The massive offering fraud w=
as also a consequence of the bank's significant lapses in internal accounti=
ng controls and repeated failure to respond to corruption risks.=E2=80=9DAn=
d DOJ:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CCredit Suisse Group AG, through its U.K. subsidiary CS=
SEL, defrauded U.S. and international investors in connection with a lendin=
g project in Mozambique,=E2=80=9D said Assistant Attorney General Kenneth A=
. Polite Jr. of the Justice Department=E2=80=99s Criminal Division. =E2=80=
=9CAmong other things, Credit Suisse Group AG, CSSEL, and their co-conspira=
tors deceived investors by hiding information about the risk that loan proc=
eeds were used for illegal purposes in connection with the restructuring of=
 the loan.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9COver the course of several years, Cre=
dit Suisse, through its subsidiary in the United Kingdom, engaged in a glob=
al criminal conspiracy to defraud investors, including investors in the Uni=
ted States, by failing to disclose material information to investors, inclu=
ding millions of dollars in kickbacks to its bankers and a high risk of cor=
ruption, in connection with an $850 million fraudulent loan to a Mozambique=
 state-owned entity,=E2=80=9D said U.S. Attorney Breon Peace for the Easter=
n District of New York.=C2=A0It is striking that the U.K. authorities talk =
about =E2=80=9Ca debt crisis and economic harm for the people of Mozambique=
=E2=80=9D while the U.S. authorities talk about =E2=80=9Cincomplete and mis=
leading disclosures=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9CU.S. and international investors.=
=E2=80=9D Everything is securities fraud, but sometimes it is also other th=
ings! But in the U.S. it is mostly securities fraud.
