      New Facebook
   =20
 =20
You know the famous line =E2=80=9Cnobody goes there anymore, it's too crowd=
ed=E2=80=9D? I sometimes think about how it would feel to run that business=
. (I believe it is traditionally a restaurant or nightclub?) On the one han=
d, you have lost your elite cachet; the people who know better, who want th=
e best of everything, who set the trends, are avoiding your product; you ha=
ve become a place for the riffraff. On the other hand you are probably maki=
ng a lot of money? From the crowds of people clamoring to get into your bus=
iness? As problems go, this seems like a=C2=A0real=C2=A0one, yes =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0plenty of luxury brands are terrified of it =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not an=
 especially=C2=A0bad=C2=A0one. Elite cachet is nice but so is money.It is s=
ome sort of pinnacle of business success =E2=80=94=C2=A0not something to as=
pire to exactly, but something to be grateful for if you achieve it =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0to have everyone in the world (1) use your product and (2) hate it=
? I don=E2=80=99t know. Anyway here=E2=80=99s a story about Facebook:Facebo=
ok is planning to change its company name next week to reflect its focus on=
 building the metaverse, according to a source with direct knowledge of the=
 matter.The coming name change, which CEO Mark Zuckerberg plans to talk abo=
ut at the company=E2=80=99s annual Connect conference on October 28th, but =
could unveil sooner, is meant to signal the tech giant=E2=80=99s ambition t=
o be known for more than social media and all the ills that entail. The reb=
rand would likely position the blue Facebook app as one of many products un=
der a parent company overseeing groups like Instagram, WhatsApp, Oculus, an=
d more. A spokesperson for Facebook declined to comment for this story.Appa=
rently =E2=80=9CHorizon=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CMeta=E2=80=9D are among the c=
andidates. I don=E2=80=99t know what the metaverse is and I intend to go as=
 long as possible without finding out, which probably means next week, but =
I prefer to read this story as =E2=80=9Cthe Facebook brand has achieved max=
imum saturation and now we=E2=80=99re starting over with something cooler.=
=E2=80=9D I also assume that if you work at Facebook Inc. and you meet some=
one and say =E2=80=9CI work at Facebook=E2=80=9D they will say =E2=80=9Cugh=
 Facebook is the worst huh=E2=80=9D and you will probably say =E2=80=9Cyep.=
=E2=80=9D Whereas if you work at Horizon Amalgamated Metaverses Inc. and yo=
u meet someone and say =E2=80=9CI work at Horizon=E2=80=9D they will say so=
mething like =E2=80=9Coh how=E2=80=99s the metaverse these days=E2=80=9D an=
d you=E2=80=99ll almost say=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cactually I work on the vaccine co=
nspiracy theory team at Horizon=E2=80=99s Facebook product=E2=80=9D but you=
=E2=80=99ll stop yourself and say =E2=80=9Coh, good, good metaverse.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0Google  did this when it  became Alphabet Inc., which had the resu=
lt that every article about it has to describe it as =E2=80=9CGoogle=E2=80=
=99s parent company Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=9D because in six years absolutely =
no normal human has ever called it anything other than =E2=80=9CGoogle.=E2=
=80=9D But Facebook has several stand-alone-ish brands that are almost as i=
mportant as Facebook Classic, plus I suppose it has a metaverse, so maybe t=
his one will take.
