I  wrote yesterday=C2=A0that, for a public-company chief executive officer,=
 =E2=80=9Carguably=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s a breach of fiduciary duties=C2=A0not=
=C2=A0to be weird on Twitter all the time.=E2=80=9D And then Jack Dorsey, t=
he chief executive officer of Twitter Inc. and Square Inc.,=C2=A0went and t=
weeted =E2=80=9C705724=E2=80=9D and it was a whole thing; here=E2=80=99s a =
Bloomberg News article titled =E2=80=9C Jack Dorsey Tweets =E2=80=98705742=
=E2=80=99 and Sets Crypto Twitter Abuzz.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a Bitcoin bl=
ock number, whatever. I cannot help but feel that he is doing it wrong but =
that=C2=A0might be my own aesthetic biases; perhaps this really is the way =
to run a public company. (Two public companies.[2]) People pretty quickly g=
uessed that it was a block number. A funnier thing to do would be just to t=
weet random numbers every once in a while and let people guess wrong. I don=
=E2=80=99t know how that would help with capital formation, but I don=E2=80=
=99t know anything anymore.
