<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Tuna bonds</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a big international bank an=
d you are hired to arrange financing for the government of Mozambique to fu=
nd a project involving fishing boats, and the government officials on the d=
eal say =E2=80=9Chey, you know what, when you raise half a billion dollars =
from investors for this project, instead of sending the money to an officia=
l government account, why don=E2=80=99t you wire it directly to our shipbui=
lding contractor in Abu Dhabi, they=E2=80=99ll handle =E2=80=A6=C2=A0a few =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0transactions for us,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s a good idea for y=
ou to do due diligence on that contractor, check them out, see what they=E2=
=80=99re all about. Ideally the due diligence report will come back saying =
=E2=80=9Cyes, that contractor is great, the guy in charge is an upstanding =
character who does scrupulous work=C2=A0for various government projects and=
 everyone he works with vouches for his integrity.=E2=80=9D But it will not=
 say that!=C2=A0Come on. It will say this:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">The Bank=E2=80=99s financial crime compliance group commissione=
d and received a third-party diligence report that quoted an anonymous sour=
ce describing the Intermediary=E2=80=99s principal (=E2=80=9CIntermediary P=
rincipal=E2=80=9D) as a =E2=80=9Cmaster of kickbacks=E2=80=9D and included =
other information, including:</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAll =
sources we spoke to about [Intermediary Principal] were confident of his pa=
st and continued involvement in offering and receiving bribes and kickbacks=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Craised concerns about the integrity of [Intermediary=
 Principal=E2=80=99s] business practices,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9C[Inter=
mediary Principal] was heavily involved in corrupt practices.=E2=80=9D</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAnother banking source close to a Leba=
nese commercial bank that previously dealt with [Intermediary Principal and=
 his brother] and the [Intermediary] group of companies stated: =E2=80=98[I=
ntermediary Principal] is a first-class deal maker and an expert in kickbac=
ks, bribery and corruption.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Yeah I mean those are probably endorsements on his LinkedIn=
. That=E2=80=99s probably=C2=A0his <em>job description </em>on LinkedIn, =
=E2=80=9CMaster of Kickbacks at Self-Employed.=E2=80=9D If you=E2=80=99re i=
n the business of shortstopping nine-figure payments between big investment=
 banks and emerging-market governmental projects, you are almost necessaril=
y in the business of diverting a big chunk of those payments for bribes. He=
re:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In total, Credit Suisse tra=
nsferred $547,463,200, including $446,950,800 that it arranged and $100,512=
,400 that was arranged by VTB, to the Intermediary, from which bank records=
 of the Intermediary reflect that improper payments were made to Mozambican=
 officials and the Intermediary Agent and others, and kickbacks to the CS B=
ankers.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shortly after the first transfer to=
 the Intermediary in March 2013, Intermediary bank records indicate transfe=
rs of over $80 million to accounts controlled by Mozambican government offi=
cials and others relating to the transaction. The transfers included a tran=
sfer of $50 million from which a relative of a high-level government offici=
al shared part of the payment with key government officials, who approved t=
he transaction and authorized the-then Minister of Finance to sign the guar=
antee. Intermediary bank records reflect additional improper payments, incl=
uding, for example, $13 million paid to government officials holding senior=
 positions at ProIndicus and a $5 million payment to a senior official who =
reported to the-then President of Mozambique.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">These quotes are from the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F=
0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjEvMzMtMTEwMDEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae68af93" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission order</a> against Credit Suis=
se Group AG, which raised a bunch of money for Mozambican government projec=
ts, much of which ended up being spent on bribes. Yesterday Credit Suisse a=
greed to pay a total of=C2=A0$475 million to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdz=
L3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0yMTM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8bbcefc2" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
the SEC</a>, the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
5405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3Yvb3BhL3ByL2NyZWRpdC1zdWlzc2Ut=
cmVzb2x2ZXMtZnJhdWR1bGVudC1tb3phbWJpcXVlLWxvYW4tY2FzZS01NDctbWlsbGlvbi1jb29=
yZGluYXRlZC1nbG9iYWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6e95847f" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">U.S. Depart=
ment of Justice</a>=C2=A0and=C2=A0the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmNhLm9yZy51ay9uZXdzL3B=
yZXNzLXJlbGVhc2VzL2NyZWRpdC1zdWlzc2UtZmluZWQtcHMxNDcxOTAyNzYtdXMyMDA2NjQ1MD=
QtYW5kLXVuZGVydGFrZXMtZmNhLWZvcmdpdmUtdXMyMDAtbWlsbGlvbi1tb3phbWJpY2FuLWRlY=
nQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc272e26" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">U.K. Financial Conduct Author=
ity</a> to settle these charges. We talked about this case <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDEtMDQvZG9uLXQtY2FsbC1icmliZ=
XMtY2hpY2tlbnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAyMDIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1=
dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMDIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN=
0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8976f64f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> back in 2019</a>; it is=
 the origin of my long-running not-legal-advice-but-still-worth-considering=
 suggestion that, if you are doing bribes, you should not call them =E2=80=
=9Cchickens.=E2=80=9D Not that you should say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m a master=
 of bribes and kickbacks=E2=80=9D either. Use=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>euphe=
misms.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked about it in 2019 because t=
hree of the Credit Suisse bankers involved in arranging the loans were arre=
sted and charged with, among other things, knowingly raising money to pay t=
hese bribes but also=C2=A0<em>taking bribes themselves</em>. (They eventual=
ly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8xMC8xOS9idXNpbmVzcy9jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3=
NlLXR1bmEtYm9uZC1maW5lcy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd9722d84" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
pleaded guilty</a>.) The basic model here is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-ty=
pe: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">Credit Suisse is a big bank and has lots of money.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Mozambique is a country and has a reasonable a=
mount of capacity to borrow money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Some Mozambican government officials would like to put millions of dollars=
 into their personal bank accounts.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">The officials could go to Credit Suisse and say =E2=80=9Cwe would like to=
 borrow money on behalf of the country of Mozambique and then steal it for =
ourselves.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But Credit Sui=
sse would say no to that proposition, because (1) that would get it in lega=
l and reputational trouble and (2) that proposition has a lot of=C2=A0<em>c=
redit risk</em>; if you lend money to a country and the money is stolen the=
 country might not be able to pay you back.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">But there=E2=80=99s not really such a thing as =E2=80=9Cgoing to =
Credit Suisse=E2=80=9D to ask for money. You go to a=C2=A0<em>person</em>=
=C2=A0at Credit Suisse.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So the off=
icials went to their friendly Credit Suisse relationship banker and said =
=E2=80=9Cwe would like to borrow money from your employer (Credit Suisse) o=
n behalf of our employer (Mozambique) and then steal it for ourselves. We n=
eed someone inside Credit Suisse to help us do that. Why not you? We will m=
ake it worth your while by giving you some of the money we steal.=E2=80=9D<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bankers were like =E2=80=9Csur=
e we could use a few million extra dollars, we will help you trick our bank=
 into lending money to Mozambique for you to steal.=E2=80=9D</li></ol><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously this is bad. Obviously the main victim he=
re is Mozambique, which has borrowed money (and has to repay it) but not re=
ceived (much of) the money because it went to bribes instead. But of course=
 the main bad actors here are the Mozambican government officials who stole=
 the money. Meanwhile the supporting bad actors here are the Credit Suisse =
bankers who helped steal the money and took bribes for their trouble. But o=
f course a secondary victim here=C2=A0<em>is Credit Suisse</em>, which was =
tricked (by its own bankers and the Mozambican officials) into making loans=
 on false pretenses that were unlikely to be paid back. Both principals her=
e are victims, and both were victimized by their own (and each others=E2=80=
=99) agents.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a third set of victim=
s here: Credit Suisse didn=E2=80=99t keep a lot of the loans on its books, =
but sold them off to other investors. (Later, it exchanged the loans into b=
onds.) The other investors were told things about the loans =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
about Mozambique=E2=80=99s borrowing capacity under IMF rules, etc., but al=
so more basically that the loans were being used to build a tuna fishing fl=
eet, not to pay bribes =E2=80=94=C2=A0that turned out not to be true. The p=
erpetrators of these lies were, you know, Credit Suisse (and its corrupt ba=
nkers) and the government of Mozambique (and its corrupt officials). If you=
 are an investor and you get an offering memo from the Republic of Mozambiq=
ue with Credit Suisse on the cover as lead arranger, and everything in the =
offering memo is a lie and the loans default, you will conclude that (1) yo=
u were defrauded and (2) Mozambique and Credit Suisse jointly did the defra=
uding. In a sense neither =E2=80=9CMozambique=E2=80=9D nor =E2=80=9CCredit =
Suisse=E2=80=9D could have done the defrauding =E2=80=94=C2=A0some particul=
ar humans employed by the government of Mozambique and Credit Suisse did th=
e defrauding =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you will not split hairs.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">One interesting question to ask, in reading these settlement=
s, is: What did Credit Suisse do wrong? One obvious possibility is: Credit =
Suisse (through its corrupt bankers) arranged to pay bribes. This is bad be=
cause it effectively stole money from the people of Mozambique to give to c=
orrupt government officials (and its own corrupt bankers). Mozambique was l=
eft with a debt that it couldn=E2=80=99t repay, and didn=E2=80=99t have muc=
h to show for it. The Credit Suisse bankers victimized the people of Mozamb=
ique, and Credit Suisse as a firm is responsible for their actions. This is=
 sort of the line that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmNhLm9yZy51ay9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2=
VzL2NyZWRpdC1zdWlzc2UtZmluZWQtcHMxNDcxOTAyNzYtdXMyMDA2NjQ1MDQtYW5kLXVuZGVyd=
GFrZXMtZmNhLWZvcmdpdmUtdXMyMDAtbWlsbGlvbi1tb3phbWJpY2FuLWRlYnQ/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cCbc272e26" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">the U.K. FCA takes</a>:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mark Steward, Executive Director of Enforcement and=
 Market Oversight at the FCA, said:</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=
=98The FCA=E2=80=99s fine reflects the impact of these tainted transactions=
 which included a debt crisis and economic harm for the people of Mozambiqu=
e. The fine would have been higher if not for Credit Suisse agreeing to pro=
vide the debt write-off of US$200 million. The FCA will continue to pursue =
serious financial crime control failings by regulated firms.=E2=80=99</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Between October 2012 to March 2016, Credit Suiss=
e failed to properly manage the risk of financial crime within its emerging=
 markets business. It had sufficient information from which it should have =
appreciated the unacceptable risk of bribery associated with the two Mozamb=
ican loans and a bond exchange related to government sponsored projects.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine Credit S=
uisse defending against this charge by saying =E2=80=9Cno, we are victims h=
ere just as much as Mozambique is; after all=C2=A0<em>we=C2=A0</em>gave <em=
>Mozambique=C2=A0</em>money under false pretenses; how were we supposed to =
know that it was for bribes?=E2=80=9D But the answer to that is, you were d=
efinitely supposed to know, there were tons of red flags. That due diligenc=
e report that I quoted at the beginning is one of them. There was actually =
some good news in that report! The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2=
FkbWluLzIwMjEvMzMtMTEwMDEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCae68af93" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
SEC says</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The information p=
rovided to the compliance team in their diligence efforts also included tha=
t the Intermediary Principal=E2=80=99s business was being conducted =E2=80=
=9Cin a more classical way, more in compliance with the rules of ethics.=E2=
=80=9D A source also reported that UAE authorities were not aware of inform=
ation tying the Intermediary to corrupt practices, and that the Intermediar=
y Principal had been removed from a screening service due to the age of som=
e of the allegations against him.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">But once you get to =E2=80=9Cmaster of kickbacks,=E2=80=9D you don=E2=
=80=99t really get to rely on conflicting reports of business conducted =E2=
=80=9Cin a more classical way.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmNhLm9yZy51=
ay9wdWJsaWNhdGlvbi9maW5hbC1ub3RpY2VzL2NyZWRpdC1zdWlzc2UtMjAyMS5wZGY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB8f26c6e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">FCA says</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse conducted due diligence, including enhan=
ced due diligence, on the relevant entities and individuals related to the =
transactions, and other key functions and committees were involved in revie=
wing and approving the transactions. However, Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s consi=
deration of the above risk factors was inadequate because it gave insuffici=
ent weight to the risk factors individually and failed to adequately consid=
er them holistically. Credit Suisse failed to recognise that a corruption =
=E2=80=98red flag=E2=80=99 will often be =E2=80=93 rather than direct evide=
nce of corruption or bribery =E2=80=93 apparent from the context of the tra=
nsaction, sector, jurisdiction and counterparty. Instead of aggregating rel=
evant risks, it considered them in isolation.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">So Credit Suisse failed to properly check on its corrupt ba=
nkers, so it is responsible for their bribes. If you take this line =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that Credit Suisse effectively stole from the people of Mozambique=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then obviously part of the punishment should be that it giv=
es the money back to Mozambique. Which is in fact <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTkvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS10by1wYXktYXQtbG=
Vhc3QtNDAwLW1pbGxpb24taW4tbW96YW1iaXF1ZS1zY2FuZGFsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjAyMV9NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTIxMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5c39275=
5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> part of the result here</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">As part of the settlement, Credit Suisse agreed to forgive $200=
 million of debt owed by Mozambique.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
=E2=80=9CThis marks a first in that relief is flowing to the people of a co=
untry,=E2=80=9D said Matthew Herrington, a lawyer for Credit Suisse at Paul=
 Hastings LLP. =E2=80=9CI am proud to have been part of this resolution.=E2=
=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A related theory of wha=
t Credit Suisse did wrong was: It let itself be taken advantage of. If your=
 view is that Credit Suisse is a victim here because it was tricked by its =
own bankers into lending money on false pretenses, that=E2=80=99s still bad=
! If you are a bank you are supposed to have processes in place to make sur=
e that your own bankers don=E2=80=99t steal from you! If they=C2=A0<em>do=
=C2=A0</em>steal from you, not only are you out the money they stole, but y=
ou=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>expect banking regulators to fine you some mor=
e money, because that is bad banking practice. Part of the job of a bank is=
 not to get its money stolen, and if you fail at that job there are legal c=
onsequences.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course it=E2=80=99s m=
ostly not Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s money that was stolen, since the loans we=
re syndicated to investors. Another possible theory of what Credit Suisse d=
id wrong=C2=A0is: Credit Suisse lied to investors about the details and leg=
ality of these loans (and bonds[1]). This is the =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2=
VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndzP=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjAyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
ZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB1a31a4eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">everything is securities fraud</a>=E2=80=
=9D theory: If you lend money to a country that will be used to pay bribes,=
 and you issue bonds to investors to fund that loan, and you don=E2=80=99t =
tell the investors about the bribes, then you have committed securities fra=
ud against them. This is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of the normal way American law=
 works these days? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and so the SEC and DOJ mostly take this l=
ine. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.=
287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0yMTM/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cC8bbcefc2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">SEC</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">"Credit Suisse provided investors with incomplete and misl=
eading disclosures despite being uniquely positioned to understand the full=
 extent of Mozambique's mounting debt and serious risk of default based on =
its prior lending arrangements," said Anita B. Bandy, Associate Director of=
 the SEC's Division of Enforcement. "The massive offering fraud was also a =
consequence of the bank's significant lapses in internal accounting control=
s and repeated failure to respond to corruption risks.=E2=80=9D</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3Yvb3BhL3B=
yL2NyZWRpdC1zdWlzc2UtcmVzb2x2ZXMtZnJhdWR1bGVudC1tb3phbWJpcXVlLWxvYW4tY2FzZS=
01NDctbWlsbGlvbi1jb29yZGluYXRlZC1nbG9iYWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC6e95847f=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">DOJ</a>:=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=
=9CCredit Suisse Group AG, through its U.K. subsidiary CSSEL, defrauded U.S=
. and international investors in connection with a lending project in Mozam=
bique,=E2=80=9D said Assistant Attorney General Kenneth A. Polite Jr. of th=
e Justice Department=E2=80=99s Criminal Division. =E2=80=9CAmong other thin=
gs, Credit Suisse Group AG, CSSEL, and their co-conspirators deceived inves=
tors by hiding information about the risk that loan proceeds were used for =
illegal purposes in connection with the restructuring of the loan.=E2=80=9D=
 =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9COver the course of seve=
ral years, Credit Suisse, through its subsidiary in the United Kingdom, eng=
aged in a global criminal conspiracy to defraud investors, including invest=
ors in the United States, by failing to disclose material information to in=
vestors, including millions of dollars in kickbacks to its bankers and a hi=
gh risk of corruption, in connection with an $850 million fraudulent loan t=
o a Mozambique state-owned entity,=E2=80=9D said U.S. Attorney Breon Peace =
for the Eastern District of New York.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">It is striking that the U.K. authorities talk about =E2=80=9C=
a debt crisis and economic harm for the people of Mozambique=E2=80=9D while=
 the U.S. authorities talk about =E2=80=9Cincomplete and misleading disclos=
ures=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9CU.S. and international investors.=E2=80=9D Everyt=
hing is securities fraud, but sometimes it is also other things! But in the=
 U.S. it is mostly securities fraud.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsore=
