, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPAC SPAC SPAC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In theory the way a special-purpose ac=
quisition company works is that a sponsor raises a pool of money from publi=
c investors, it finds a private company to take public, it gives the privat=
e company the money, the public investors in the SPAC get shares of the pri=
vate company and the private company is now public. This theory basically w=
orked earlier in 2021; a lot of companies went public this way at high valu=
ations and raised lots of money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These days=
 though <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.2=
87773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktM=
jgvd2VsbHMtZmFyZ28tc3dhcHBlZC1zb21lLWRpZ2l0cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDIwMjFfTU9ORVlT=
VFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTE=
wMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBecd90b57" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> the way a SPAC often works</a> is that a sponsor raises a pool of mon=
ey from investors, it finds a private company to take public, it=C2=A0<em>g=
ives the money back to the investors</em>, and the private company is now p=
ublic. The money comes, the money goes; it's just a weird sort of certifica=
te of deposit for the investors and a vague sign of seriousness for the SPA=
C sponsor. SPAC investors are allowed to withdraw their money once the deal=
 is announced, and these days they often do. Redemption rates of 97% are no=
t unheard of; a $200 million SPAC might end up with only $6 million in cash=
 to give to its merger target.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But th=
e normal way that a SPAC works is that there is a PIPE =E2=80=94=C2=A0a pri=
vate investment in public equity =E2=80=94=C2=A0alongside the SPAC. Big ins=
titutional investors commit to buying stock, typically at the same price as=
 the SPAC, in order to give the target company more certainty. So if you si=
gn up a deal with a $200 million SPAC, you might also line up $150 million =
of investments from strategic partners, big investment funds, hedge funds, =
etc. Then when the deal closes you=E2=80=99ll get $150 million of committed=
 money plus $200 million or $50 million or $3 million or whatever of SPAC m=
oney. The SPAC money is uncertain but you at least have some guaranteed mon=
ey.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In theory you could get rid of the PIPE=
 too and just do a SPAC deal where you raise like $6 million and become a p=
ublic company. That hardly seems worth it. You do get a public listing; tha=
t=E2=80=99s something. You pay the SPAC sponsor a lot for it though. It see=
ms to me that if you want to list on the stock exchange without raising any=
 money, you might as well just do a direct listing; that's a thing you can =
do now. But I suppose there is some set of companies that would be happy en=
ough to go public by merging with a SPAC with no money in it.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s a funny <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2=
NvbnRlbnQvNjY3NWFjMWUtYTlhMC00OGQ4LWI0ZTktYWVlMmVmMjdjN2Jl/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB1e90b679" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Financial Times story</a> about a SPAC merger wh=
ere the lead PIPE investor just vanished:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The Metals Company has big ambitions to mine the depths of the P=
acific Ocean for rare earth metals used to power everything from iPhones to=
 electric vehicles. The problem is that it is short on cash.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The Canadian start-up went public last month through a sp=
ecial purpose acquisition company but has been left high and dry by one inv=
estor who was meant to hand over 60 per cent of $330m it had been counting =
on to start digging but has now all but disappeared.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The $200m hole left in the The Metals Company=E2=80=99s books by =
Ramas Capital Management, a little-known private equity firm run by former =
JPMorgan Chase analyst Ganesh Betanabhatla, has also raised deeper question=
s about the funding model underpinning the Spac playbook.</p></blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the company (then called DeepGreen Metals =
Inc.) <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287=
773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3OTg1NjIvMDAwMTI=
xMzkwMDIxMDEzMzQ4L2VhMTM3MDAxZXg5OS0xX3N1c3RhaW5hYmxlLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB7cf98eb1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">announced its deal</a>=C2=A0with a SPAC calle=
d SOAC (Sustainable Opportunities Acqusition Corp.) back in March, a happie=
r time for SPACs, it was a $300 million SPAC deal plus a $330 million =E2=
=80=9Cfully committed=E2=80=9D PIPE, for a total of $660 million. It ended =
up <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25405870.287773=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3OTg1NjIvMDAwMTIxMz=
kwMDIxMDQ2ODAyL2VhMTQ2Nzc5ZXg5OS0xX3N1c3RhaW5hYmxlLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB10219f14" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">getting $137 million</a>: 90% of the SPAC investor=
s withdrew, leaving only $27.2 million in the pot, which is fairly common t=
hese days, but also only $110.1 million of the $330 million PIPE money actu=
ally came through, which is not really supposed to happen. =E2=80=9CFully c=
ommitted.=E2=80=9D Oops! The FT says:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Companies and their advisers are, as part of the due diligence proce=
ss, expected to ensure that Pipe investors have enough cash to fulfil their=
 obligations. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Metals Company said B=
etanabhatla provided documentation that showed Ramas had a $1.5bn natural r=
esources fund backed by a sovereign wealth fund. Another person who was pre=
sent during the meetings said the energy investor assured the company it ha=
d drawn =E2=80=9Csufficient funds to fulfil its $200m commitment=E2=80=9D.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDue diligence on Ramas included th=
e review of the agreements with the fund=E2=80=99s [limited partners] and r=
epresentation that cash already in Ramas=E2=80=99s control was well in exce=
ss of their Pipe commitment,=E2=80=9D the company said.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn fact, allocations for other Pipe investors were cu=
t back to make additional room for Ramas given their strategic contribution=
s, such was the confidence of SOAC=E2=80=99s advisers in the due diligence =
process,=E2=80=9D it added.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=
